recommandationVideos.Title: Finland's üá´üáÆ impact on NATO
Keywords: the impact of finland in nato
recommandationVideos.Description:
Russia‚Äôs full-scale invasion of Ukraine in 2022, against the backdrop of its illegal annexation of Crimea in 2014, changed the security landscape in Europe and acted as a catalyst for Finland‚Äôs accession to NATO. After 30 years of close partnership with NATO, Finland joined the Alliance as a new member in April 2023.

With its geographic proximity to Russia, Finland shares a 1,300-km border with Russia and has a history of facing Russian aggression. Russia‚Äôs unprovoked and brutal full-scale war on Ukraine got Finland to rethink its defence strategy, and abandon its policy of military non-alignment. While Finland now benefits from the protection of NATO membership and the collective defence clause (‚Äúone for all, all for one‚Äù) under Article 5 of NATO‚Äôs founding treaty (also called the Washington Treaty), Finland‚Äôs membership also strengthens NATO‚Äôs collective deterrence and defence and the security of the Euro-Atlantic area.

Despite having a small population of 5.5 million, Finland has an impressive wartime strength of 280,000 military personnel, and that is due to its comprehensive conscription service. The country also counts on strong artillery capabilities, a fleet of modern fighter jets, powerful mine hunting capabilities at sea and much more.

Finland is also situated in a potentially vulnerable area, including both the High North and the Baltic Sea, regions of high strategic importance. In this video, we look at what NATO membership means for Finland, and how the country contributes to the security of our Alliance.

recommandationVideos.Title: Arctic War at Sea ‚Äì Finland‚Äôs Impact on NATO
recommandationVideos.Description:
Exercise Freezing Winds 23 led by the Finnish Navy was the first major naval exercise led by Finland as a NATO member.

Arctic environment of high north during the coldest winter period of Finland poses extreme challenges to overcome in maritime operations. The allied exercise involved protecting the Finnish coast and sea lines of communication by conducting maritime operations together with allies and partners.

Together we protect the Baltic Sea area in all domains of maritime security.

#StrongerTogether #WeAreNATO #Navyfi #Merivoimat

Vigilant Fox -harjoitus j√§rjestettiin 25‚Äî29.7.2022.

Harjoitus kokonaisuudessaan oli monipuolinen sek√§ laaja, niin osallistuvien joukkojen kuin taktiikoidenkin osalta. Vaativasta harjoituksesta huolimatta valmisyksik√∂iden toiminta oli vakuuttavaa ja n√§kyi saumattomana yhteisty√∂n√§ eri yksik√∂iden ja maiden v√§lill√§. Vigilant Fox osoitti, ett√§ kesken√§√§n yhteensopivat, mutta silti erilaiset joukot pystyv√§t t√§ydent√§m√§√§n toisiaan tehokkaasti.

üá´üáÆ üá∫üá∏ üá¨üáß The goal of exercise Vigilant Fox was to develop the readiness and performance of Readiness Units and to combine the operational methods of the tactical level of different countries and units. The total strength of the exercise was approximately 750 persons and the exercise was led by Army Command Finland. The exercise was organized at the Pohjankangas training area in Niinisalo. Participants of Exercise Vigilant Fox included the readiness units from Pori Brigade, Guard Jaeger Regiment and Karelia Brigade, as well as our international partners from the United States and the United Kingdom. Exercise Vigilant Fox lasted from 25th of July until the 29th of July 2022.

The exercise was both versatile and extensive in terms of participating troops and tactics During the exercise, the Readiness Units of the Army have fought both on the same side and against each other. All parties got to experience each other's operating methods and combine their performance. Despite the demanding training, the performance of the Readiness Units was convincing and created great cooperation between the different units and countries. Vigilant Fox proved that compatible, yet different forces can complement each other effectively.

Cooperation between units was close and intense through the exercise. Readiness, capabilities and interoperability improved significantly together with our international partners during the past week. The goals given to this exercise were achieved.

By practising together, we can develop the capabilities of all sides. Now and in the future.

recommandationVideos.Title: Finland's üá´üáÆ impact on NATO
Keywords: the impact of finland in nato
recommandationVideos.Description:
Russia‚Äôs full-scale invasion of Ukraine in 2022, against the backdrop of its illegal annexation of Crimea in 2014, changed the security landscape in Europe and acted as a catalyst for Finland‚Äôs accession to NATO. After 30 years of close partnership with NATO, Finland joined the Alliance as a new member in April 2023.

With its geographic proximity to Russia, Finland shares a 1,300-km border with Russia and has a history of facing Russian aggression. Russia‚Äôs unprovoked and brutal full-scale war on Ukraine got Finland to rethink its defence strategy, and abandon its policy of military non-alignment. While Finland now benefits from the protection of NATO membership and the collective defence clause (‚Äúone for all, all for one‚Äù) under Article 5 of NATO‚Äôs founding treaty (also called the Washington Treaty), Finland‚Äôs membership also strengthens NATO‚Äôs collective deterrence and defence and the security of the Euro-Atlantic area.

Despite having a small population of 5.5 million, Finland has an impressive wartime strength of 280,000 military personnel, and that is due to its comprehensive conscription service. The country also counts on strong artillery capabilities, a fleet of modern fighter jets, powerful mine hunting capabilities at sea and much more.

Finland is also situated in a potentially vulnerable area, including both the High North and the Baltic Sea, regions of high strategic importance. In this video, we look at what NATO membership means for Finland, and how the country contributes to the security of our Alliance.

recommandationVideos.Description:
Exercise Freezing Winds 23 led by the Finnish Navy was the first major naval exercise led by Finland as a NATO member.

EN:
A Strong Reservist Presence in Keh√§ 22 Local Defence Exercise. 

The year‚Äôs second local defence exercise led by the Guard Jaeger Regiment, Keh√§ 22, was organized in the Helsinki metropolitan area and in Western Uusimaa. The strength of the training units was around 1,100 consisting of conscripts, reservists and regular personnel. The exercise was led by the Deputy Commander of the Guard Jaeger Regiment, Colonel Vesa Laitonen. 

The exercise included training of local-level inter-agency cooperation with the goal of enhancing operating capabilities between agencies. Authorities in the exercise included the West Uusimaa Police Department and L√§nsi-Uusimaa Rescue Department, as well as the municipal authorities of Espoo, Hanko and Kirkonummi. A total of some 700 reservists participated in the exercise. It was the largest number of reservists participating in an exercise led by the Guard Jaeger Regiment since 2019. This exercise was the final field training exercise of the rank-and-file military police troops and to some in the Reconnaissance Company of the Sports School, who muster out in September. The exercise units mainly operated in the Helsinki metropolitan area and Western Uusimaa. The locations included Helsinki, Espoo, Kauniainen, Kirkkonummi, Raasepori and Hanko. 

Keh√§ 22 was a part of a continuum of local defence exercises. Local defence exercises are organized twice a year across Finland. In these exercises, focus is placed on developing local forces‚Äô performance and training of cooperation with various authorities.
